entry.title: Add CSS filter string support as parameter for beginLayer
entry.content:
This change adds support for using a CSS filter string as the input

parameter for beginLayer. the IDL definition for CanvasFilterInput was

modified to allow the use of a DOMString as the filter when beginLayer

is called.



A new method in CanvasFilterOperationResolver was added for creating the

filter operations for this type of input, since it requires access to

the font value (for units that depend on the font) and potentially to a

style resolution host if possible.



Given that the CanvasFilterInput IDL is shared with the CanvasFilter

object, the creation of these objects was modified to also allow the use

of a CSS filter string.



WPT tests were added to verify the behavior of these filters and their

interaction when nested within a layer with a filter that uses a

dictionary. Unit tests were added for the new functions.

entry.title: [PageColors] Integration of PageColors feature with NativeTheme
entry.content:
This CL makes relevant state changes to the NativeTheme web instance

when Page colors changes. This is done in the

ColorSchemeNativeThemeObserver::OnNativeThemeUpdated method.



In the ColorSchemeNativeThemeObserver::OnNativeThemeUpdated method,

we preserves the current behavior if Page Colors is 'Off' and forced

colors is false OR forced colors is true and Page Colors is

'High Contrast'. However, if that is not the case then:



1. Page Colors is 'Off' and forced colors is true, we override the

state of forced colors for the native theme instance for web since the

Page colors browser setting takes precedence over OS for web content.

Here, we also watch for changes to the preferred color scheme and make

sure we adjust the state appropriately.

2. Page Colors is one of the Contrast themes i.e. 'Dusk', 'Desert',

'Black', 'White'. Here, we set the forced colors state to true and

other states appropriately for web content.



This CL adds the color scheme observer as a native theme observer for

Linux in order to receive the correct state changes from

NativeThemeAura.

entry.title: Revert "[a11y] Move some of serialization pipeline from RAI to cache."
entry.content:
This reverts commit b0fb6c7b87c7ba95326a9d7a2bb30e9d055ec315.



Reason for revert: crbug.com/1505157



Original change's description:

> [a11y] Move some of serialization pipeline from RAI to cache.

>

> This CL aims to start moving some of the code path starting from HandleAXEvent to ScheduleImmediateAXUpdate over to cache side. The old code is still left in RAI for legacy support.

>

> The aim is to eventually delete the code from RAI side, and then RAI would only be called from ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents to AXReadyCallback.

>

> ----------------------------

> Details (only explaining post-lifecyle mode):

> Before this CL, a11y events (kind of) go like this: AXObjectCacheImpl::PostPlatformNotification -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::HandleAXEvent which also calls AXObjectCacheImpl::AddPendingEvent --> RenderAccessibilityImpl::ScheduleImmediateAXUpdate -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleAXUpdate --> AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback

>

> Note that -> doesn't mean direct calls. Some calls in the middle may have been skipped. The CL prevents these excessively unnecessary calls in between RAI (RenderAccessibilityImpl) and AXObjectCacheImpl. The calls now go like this (again kinda): AXObjectCacheImpl::PostPlatformNotification -> AXObjectCacheImpl::AddEventToSerializationQueue -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleImmediateSerialization -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleAXUpdate -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback

>

> Notice how RAI is only called at the very end. Of course, to make this possible many of the side logic had to be moved too like the delaying code that used to be AXReadyCallback is now at AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents.

>

> This image describes the above: https://i.imgur.com/U3tODTX.png

> What the CL achieves is moving the code in the blue square over to the left-hand side, thus making the code stay in AXObjectCache longer and only move to RAI at RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback. The serialization delay is moved to ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents.

>

> ----------------------------

> Legacy scheduling mode (as opposed to post-lifecycle serialization) still uses the old code which goes back and forth between RAI and AXObjectCache. The reason they were not moved as well is that legacy mode will get removed eventually anyway. When legacy mode is removed, we can safely remove the old code from RAI.

>

> ----------------------------

> Also, with the cleaner code, it'll be feasible to change the scheduling logic further to limit some events like scrolling. Scrolling improvements discussed here https://docs.google.com/document/d/1fBK1BBrG8souqZpyv7q_3kxCYF1IYoXNPXmoVL7X8Gk/edit#heading=h.uo8ebdp7cxl

>

> ----------------------------

entry.title: Launch SubprocessMetricsAsync
entry.content:
In particular, it enables the feature with the following params:

- "PeriodicMergeAsync" set to true. I.e., when merging subprocess

metrics for periodic ongoing logs, it will be done asynchronously.

- "DeregisterAsync" set to true. I.e., when a subprocess exits, and

we merge its metrics one last time, it will be done asynchronously.

- "DeregisterSequenced" set to false. I.e., when there are multiple

tasks to merge subprocess metrics (maybe multiple subprocesses

exited at the same time), they will be run in parallel, and not in

sequence. For example, when the browser is shutting down.



This has made great improvements on Android Scroll Jank.

entry.title: [history] HistoryBackend::AddPage - Remove a failing DCHECK
entry.content:
There's a DCHECK that assumes that the referrer URL is the same as the

first URL in the redirect chain.



This fails very rarely, but it does fail sometimes, for unknown

reasons, as evidenced in the bug's crash reports.



It happens across all platforms at a low rate of one or two crashes per

day across users that have DCHECKs turned on.



We've seen evidence that there's a low level of History database

corruption across all users at all times, so this could be the reason.

Or, there could be a caller to AddPage where HistoryAddPageArgs is

improperly populated.



Instead of crashing because of the DCHECK, this CL proposes that Chrome

simply continues on to update the transition of the previous visit.



Indeed that WAS the production behavior of Chrome before DCHECK in

production was turned on.

entry.title: Update all instances of the progress indicator to rounded caps
entry.content:
Previously, we only had rounded caps for the app list and shelf apps

progress indicators. To keep consistency across surfaces, make the

round caps as the default strategy to paint the progress indicator.



Additionally, modify the painting algorithm to adapt to the rounded caps:



- For drawing the arc during the pending animation, if start < end,

instead of drawing two paths created by CreatePathSegment(), generate

both paths separately and join them, so only one path is drawn and the

intersection is accounted as part of the path.



- For drawing at 0 progress, skip creating a path in CreatePathSegment()

if start == end to make sure that nothing is drawn, since the rounded

caps may be drawn at a zero-length segment.



See bug for screen recording of the result.

entry.title: [Fuchsia] Implement serial-boot to reboot via fastboot and serialio
entry.content:
The tool can also be used to replace dmc & dms.

It provides excessive benefits,

1) We have one way to flash, i.e. with lockfile.

2) We have one way to access the serial port, i.e. through serialio.

3) We have one way to reboot the device, i.e. through

serialio + dm or fastboot.

4) We have one way to detect the state of the device, i.e.

through serialio + echo or fastboot.

5) None of the above operations require ssh access to the device and

can be used to recover from a bad image.



And we really do not need to reinvent the wheel to provide local flash

support for the eng: sonic has the full set of functionality to flash

a prebuilt or local image easily; `ffx target flash` can also be used.

entry.title: [Exo] Add a new request to apply rounded corners to the window's
entry.content:
shadow



This CL adds a new Wayland protocol to Aura Shell to allow clients to

specify the radius of a window's shadow.



Previously, when we introduced the protocol to round the corners of

a window, we would match the radii of the shadow to the radii of the

window specified by the client. However, this protocol was only used

by clients that do server-side decoration.



Clients that do client-side decoration, such as Lacros, would never call

this protocol, so the server had no way to know if it should round the

shadow. This new protocol addresses this issue.

entry.title: Rename {absl => std}::optional in //ash/
entry.content:
Automated patch, intended to be effectively a no-op.



Context:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/cxx/c/nBD_1LaanTc/m/ghh-ZZhWAwAJ?utm_medium=email&utm_source=footer



As of https://crrev.com/1204351, absl::optional is now a type alias for

std::optional. We should migrate toward it.



Script:

```

function replace {

echo "Replacing $1 by $2"

git grep -l "$1" \

| cut -f1 -d: \

| grep \

-e "^ash" \

| sort \

| uniq \

| grep \

-e "\.h" \

-e "\.cc" \

-e "\.mm" \

-e "\.py" \

| xargs sed -i "s/$1/$2/g"

}

replace "absl::make_optional" "std::make_optional"

replace "absl::optional" "std::optional"

replace "absl::nullopt" "std::nullopt"

replace "absl::in_place" "std::in_place"

replace "absl::in_place_t" "std::in_place_t"

replace "\"third_party\/abseil-cpp\/absl\/types\/optional.h\"" ""

git cl format

```
